What is a DataFrame ?¶

A Dataframe is a table of data that contains a collection of Rows and Columns.

Series are one-dimensional objects DataFrames are two-dimensional : "labeled Indices" and "Columns"

Now we will be working with Two-dimensional Datasets.

What is a Dimension?¶

If you look at a Series , it extends in only one direction.

  • Working with series we would need at the most one piece of information. Example : To select any value in the Series, we would need to specify either the Index Label or the index position
In [12]:
ser
Out[12]:
0       Olga
1     Andrew
2      Brian
3    Telulah
4     Nicole
5      Tilda
Name: name, dtype: object
In [13]:
#Example : If we are interested in 'Brian' we would say "index position 2"
ser.iloc[2]
Out[13]:
'Brian'

But if we try to access "Brian" from the below dataframe , we would have to specify the index position [2] as well as the column position [0]

In [14]:
df
Out[14]:
name age married
0 Olga 29 False
1 Andrew 21 True
2 Brian 45 True
3 Telulah 23 True
4 Nicole 39 False
5 Tilda 46 True
In [15]:
df.iloc[2,0]
Out[15]:
'Brian'

.ndim¶

It gives us the number of dimensions

In [16]:
ser.ndim
Out[16]:
1
In [17]:
df.ndim
Out[17]:

.shape¶

In [18]:
ser.shape
Out[18]:
(6,)
  • We have 6 records in our Series
In [19]:

Out[19]:
(6, 3)
  • 6 rows and 3 columns
  • A Series has only labeled Indices
  • DataFrames have labeled Indices and Columns
  • Each column in a DataFrame is a Series
  • think of Dataframe as a Collection of Series

More ways of creating DataFrame¶

Build a DataFrame from Tuples¶

In [30]:
#we convert all three lists to tuples
#Remember both lists and tuples are ordered and iterable but
#Unlike lists Tuples are Immutable
tuple_names = tuple(names)
tuple_ages = tuple(ages)
tuple_married = tuple(married)
In [32]:
#This is a Tuple
tuple_names
Out[32]:
('Olga', 'Andrew', 'Brian', 'Telulah', 'Nicole', 'Tilda')

names
Out[33]:
['Olga', 'Andrew', 'Brian', 'Telulah', 'Nicole', 'Tilda']

             'married' : tuple_married})

Build DataFrame from Dictionary of Dictionaries¶

In [38]:
pd.DataFrame({'names' : {0 : 'Olga' , 1 : 'Andrew'}})
Out[38]:
names
0 Olga
1 Andrew
In [40]:
#We use a built-in Python function called "enumerate" 
#which is like an Iterator with "counter" combined
#Using enumerate we will traverse all the three lists as well as access each item's Position at the same time
#The below code just gives us a place in memory
enumerate(names)
Out[40]:
<enumerate at 0x208fadceac0>
In [41]:
#We will wrap it in a list
list(enumerate(names))
Out[41]:
[(0, 'Olga'),
 (1, 'Andrew'),
 (2, 'Brian'),
 (3, 'Telulah'),
 (4, 'Nicole'),
 (5, 'Tilda')]
  • enumerator is an iterator that gets us pairs of tuples containing the value of each item as well as its position in the iterable (which is the list here) , which is exactly what we need to create dictionaries
  • we want to get the output in this format
  • {0 : 'Olga' , 1 : 'Andrew'}})
In [42]:
names
Out[42]:
['Olga', 'Andrew', 'Brian', 'Telulah', 'Nicole', 'Tilda']
In [43]:
#We use Dictionary comprehension to create Key value pairs
dict_names = {k:v for k,v in enumerate(names)}
In [44]:
dict_names
Out[44]:
{0: 'Olga', 1: 'Andrew', 2: 'Brian', 3: 'Telulah', 4: 'Nicole', 5: 'Tilda'}
In [45]:
dict_ages = {k:v for k,v in enumerate(ages)}
dict_married = {k:v for k,v in enumerate(married)}

We can also define a function for the above exercise¶

In [48]:
def convert_list_to_dict(l):
    return{k:v for k,v in enumerate(l)}
In [49]:
dict_names = convert_list_to_dict(names)
In [50]:
dict_ages = convert_list_to_dict(ages)
In [51]:
dict_married = convert_list_to_dict(married)
In [52]:
dict_names
Out[52]:
{0: 'Olga', 1: 'Andrew', 2: 'Brian', 3: 'Telulah', 4: 'Nicole', 5: 'Tilda'}
In [53]:
dict_ages
Out[53]:
{0: 29, 1: 21, 2: 45, 3: 23, 4: 39, 5: 46}
In [55]:
dict_married
Out[55]:
{0: False, 1: True, 2: True, 3: True, 4: False, 5: True}

All the above methods used a Column-wise approach to build the DataFrame

We can also use a Row-wise approach

List of Dicts¶

In [57]:
#This is how we create the first Row

pd.DataFrame([{
    'name' : 'Olga',
    'age' : 29,
    'married' : False
}])
Out[57]:
name age married
0 Olga 29 False

We use the Zip method here . It combines values from more than one Iterable into a List of Tuples.¶

In [59]:
names
Out[59]:
['Olga', 'Andrew', 'Brian', 'Telulah', 'Nicole', 'Tilda']
In [60]:
ages
Out[60]:
[29, 21, 45, 23, 39, 46]
In [61]:
married
Out[61]:
[False, True, True, True, False, True]
In [58]:
list(zip(names , ages , married))
Out[58]:
[('Olga', 29, False),
 ('Andrew', 21, True),
 ('Brian', 45, True),
 ('Telulah', 23, True),
 ('Nicole', 39, False),
 ('Tilda', 46, True)]
In [62]:
rowwise = [{'name' : name , 'age' : ages , 'married' : married} for name, ages, married in zip(names , ages , married)]
In [63]:
rowwise
Out[63]:
[{'name': 'Olga', 'age': 29, 'married': False},
 {'name': 'Andrew', 'age': 21, 'married': True},
 {'name': 'Brian', 'age': 45, 'married': True},
 {'name': 'Telulah', 'age': 23, 'married': True},
 {'name': 'Nicole', 'age': 39, 'married': False},
 {'name': 'Tilda', 'age': 46, 'married': True}]
In [64]:
#we pass it to the DataFrame Constructor
pd.DataFrame(rowwise)
Out[64]:
name age married
0 Olga 29 False
1 Andrew 21 True
2 Brian 45 True
3 Telulah 23 True
4 Nicole 39 False
5 Tilda 46 True

Sampling with Replacement or Weights¶

Whenever we sample records from our population , we replace that record , so the probability of picking the same record again remains unchanged.

Think of sampling as choosing something from a hat and the hat contains all the possible values in our population. When we sample with replacement , we choose to put this record that we just selected back into the hat. The idea is to exact same record multiple times. This is also known as "BootStrapping" in Statistics

Above you can see we end up choosing the same element more than once.

Sampling with or without Replacement¶

Weighted Sampling¶

The Probability of choosing any one sample or element from the set is Equal.

Here we label our samples with specific weights and then we take those weights into consideration when we do the ' sampling.

In [122]:
#We create a Pandas series and assign it to the "weights" variable.
#To the "data" parameter , we specify the weights
#We call these relative weights because Pandas will normalize it behind the scenes anyway
#In other words these weights don't necessarily have to add up 1 or 100% 
#To the index parameter , we pass the values that im interested in sampling by referencing their Index Labels
In [123]:
weights = pd.Series(data = [10, 10, 10, 1, 2] , index = [7 , 17 , 29 , 5 , 6])

How are Random Numbers Generated¶

How does Pandas decide which Random record or number to pick. How does pandas decide to give us an observation with index label 4816 below:

In [140]:
nutri.sample()
Out[140]:
name serving_size calories total_fat saturated_fat cholesterol sodium choline folate folic_acid ... fat saturated_fatty_acids monounsaturated_fatty_acids polyunsaturated_fatty_acids fatty_acids_total_trans alcohol ash caffeine theobromine water
4816 Beef, baked, cooked, loaf, 80% lean meat / 20%... 100 g 254 16g 6.2g 88mg 67.00 mg 80.9 mg 7.00 mcg 0.00 mcg ... 16.17 g 6.159 g 7.189 g 0.471 g 88.00 mg 0.0 g 0.90 g 0.00 mg 0.00 mg 57.70 g

1 rows × 76 columns

True Randomness is when we cannot predict what comes next . But Python and Numpy both use Pseudo-Random Number Generators called "Mersenne Twister"

When we set random_state = "some number" , we are essentially locking down the starting input, we are starting our PRNG from the same point . But, because our PRNG is deterministic , a sequence of numbers that it generates when fed this random state will always be the same. That is why we are guaranteed that whenever we sample with a given random_state we will always get the same sample.

In [281]:
#We want to select all the numeric characters
#How to do that?
#In Regex we can use character Sets
#A Character Set allows us to match one of several characters and in Regex they are defines using Square brackets
#And within those Square brackets we will define a range of Characters , all the letters going from a to z => [a-z]
#Also add fro upper case as well => [a-zA-Z]

In [282]:
#But remember our purpose was to capture anything that is not a unit
#Somehow we need to Flip this around
#In Regex it is as easy as negating the entire character set , so we add a CARAT symbol after the Square bracket
#=> [^a-zA-Z]

In [284]:

#We get a new df with all the numeric values removed and only units remaining

DataFrame .dropna()¶

dropna() method excludes all null values from given Series

  • In DataFrames we need to specify the axis
In [323]:
df
Out[323]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
1 13.0 34.5 1.74
2 14.0 83.2 1.91
3 16.0 90.1 1.54

https://www.udemy.com/course/the-ultimate-pandas-bootcamp-advanced-python-data-analysis/learn/lecture/18639862#overview

In [324]:
#currently it does not have a null value ,lets insert
df.loc[2, 'weight'] = np.nan
In [325]:
df
Out[325]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
1 13.0 34.5 1.74
2 14.0 NaN 1.91
3 16.0 90.1 1.54
In [327]:
#Row : 1 and all columns
df.loc[1 , :] = np.nan
In [328]:
df
Out[328]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
1 NaN NaN NaN
2 14.0 NaN 1.91
3 16.0 90.1 1.54
In [329]:
#Now we have atleast one NAN in each column
In [331]:
#dropna() without specifying the axis
#it works exactly as df.dropna(how = 'any' , axis = 0)
#default is the Row axis
df.dropna()
Out[331]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
3 16.0 90.1 1.54
  • All NANs from any row and column got removed
  • Row 1 and Row 2 is completely gone
In [333]:
#axis = 0 is for Rows 
df.dropna(how = 'any' , axis = 0)
Out[333]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
3 16.0 90.1 1.54

For axis = 0 (Row)

  • how = all : Drop rows only if all values in the Rows are Null
  • how = any : Drop rows only if any value in the Rows is Null

For axis = 1 (Column)

  • how = all : Drop Columns only if all values in the columns are Null
  • how = any : Drop Columns only if any value in the columns is Null
In [334]:
#axis = 1 is for columns 
df.dropna(how = 'any' , axis = 1)
Out[334]:
0
1
2
3
In [335]:
#axis = 0 is for rows 
df.dropna(how = 'all' , axis = 0)
Out[335]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
2 14.0 NaN 1.91
3 16.0 90.1 1.54
In [336]:
#axis = 1 is for columns 
df.dropna(how = 'all' , axis = 1)
Out[336]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
1 NaN NaN NaN
2 14.0 NaN 1.91
3 16.0 90.1 1.54
In [ ]:
how parameter allows us to set a condition as to what should be dropped or excluded

thresh parameter¶

  • thresh() allows us to fine tune this dropping condition .
  • thresh() is short for threshold
  • thresh give us an opportunity to specifically say , how many non-na values we want in a given sequence, it could be a row or column
  • With the thresh parameter we are setting the inclusion condition, the minimum number of non-na values that we want to be included
In [338]:
#We want Rows (axis = 0) with only 3 non-na values
#this is same as df.dropna(how = 'any' , axis =0)
df.dropna(thresh = 3 , axis =0)
Out[338]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
3 16.0 90.1 1.54
In [339]:
df.shape #We have 4 rows and 3 columns
Out[339]:
(4, 3)
In [341]:
df.shape[1] #only column shape
Out[341]:
3
In [342]:
#If we want to select the number of columns dynamically and say we want to have as many non-na values
#as there are columns in the df
#We want the drop condition to be applied to the row axis
df.dropna(thresh = df.shape[1] ,axis = 0)
Out[342]:
age weight height
0 12.0 41.1 1.72
3 16.0 90.1 1.54
In [344]:
#if we simply pass the axis = 1
#This is equivalent to df.dropna(how = 'any' , axis = 1)

Out[344]:
0

#Since each column in our df has atleast one non-na value

the subset parameter¶

#equivalent to df.dropna(axis = 0 , how = 'any', subset = 'gender')

Note :¶

  • When the axis parameter is 1 (that is Column) , the subset parameter will take Row labels
  • When the axis parameter is 0 (that is Row) , the subset parameter will take Column labels

Facts about Sodium and Potassium for Good Health :¶

With few exceptions, a healthier diet should be lower in sodium and higher in potassium.

a healthier diet should be lower in sodium and higher in potassium.

In fact, lowering dietary sodium intake and increasing potassium intake (resulting in a lower sodium potassium ratio) is an integral strategy of national and international public health goals.

Thus, a diet with high quality produces a low sodium potassium ratio (generally less than the number 1)

Over 70% of our sodium intake is derived from packaged, preprepared, or restaurant foods

To calculate the sodium to potassium ratio, simply divide the amount of sodium by the amount of potassium

K_to_NA = (nutri.potassium_mg / nutri.sodium_mg)

In order to avoid division by 0 , we will replace all zeros with ones in the whole series

In [ ]:
K_to_NA = (nutri.potassium_mg.replace(0,1) / nutri.sodium_mg.replace(0,1))
